left to right direction
hide empty description
state "Observe" as observe
state "EvaluateReady" as evaluate_ready
state "Ready" as ready
state "Retryable" as retryable
state "Failed" as failed
observe : read spec, tracked status, delete intent,\nand current OCI lifecycle
state "ResolveByLookup" as resolve_by_lookup
state "RejectUnsupportedDrift" as reject_unsupported_drift
state "ApplyUpdate" as apply_update
state "DeletePending" as delete_pending
state "Deleted" as deleted
state "DeleteCleanupBlocked" as delete_cleanup_blocked
[*] --> observe : CreateSchedule
observe --> resolve_by_lookup : tracked identity missing
resolve_by_lookup --> evaluate_ready : lookup or create reaches\nACTIVE, INACTIVE
resolve_by_lookup --> failed : unresolved OCI error or non-success state
observe --> evaluate_ready : OCI state in ACTIVE,\nINACTIVE
observe --> failed : unresolved OCI error or non-success state
evaluate_ready --> reject_unsupported_drift : force-new or conflicting\ndrift detected
reject_unsupported_drift --> ready : wait for spec or live state change
evaluate_ready --> apply_update : supported mutable drift for\ndefined_tags, description,\nfreeform_tags (+2 more)
apply_update --> ready : update path completes
evaluate_ready --> ready : no supported drift remains
ready --> ready : no supported drift remains
retryable --> retryable : OCI remains retryable
failed --> failed : OCI remains terminal
ready --> delete_pending : delete requested
retryable --> delete_pending : delete requested
failed --> delete_pending : delete requested
delete_pending --> delete_cleanup_blocked : cleanup or finalizer release remains blocked
delete_cleanup_blocked --> deleted : retry delete completion until allowed
deleted --> deleted : terminal stutter
note right of ready
shared diagram:
shared/diagrams/shared-controller-state-machine.svg
Start from the shared controller phase model and
specialize imported provider states, delete
targets, and failure exits here.
archetype batch: Generated service-manager
controllers map provider states into the shared
controller phases with explicit finalizer and
requeue policies.
service: usageapi
slug: schedule
kind: Schedule
archetype: generated-service-manager
status/finalizer: required /
retain-until-confirmed-delete
requeue: terminating
provider states: create none; update none;
delete none
supported drift: defined_tags, description,
freeform_tags, output_file_format (+1 more)
reject before mutate: force-new fields
compartment_id, name, query_properties,
saved_report_id (+2 more)
create-only fields: none
list lookup: oci_usage_schedules filters name
conflicts: none
open gaps: none
The generated runtime reuses an existing
schedule by listing on the required
compartmentId request scope plus the exact
schedule name, then binding on that unique name
before GetSchedule loads the full payload for
drift evaluation.
The Usage API exposes lifecycleState on Schedule
bodies, so create and update settle without a
service-local synchronous wrapper; both ACTIVE
and INACTIVE are modeled as steady
resource-exists states.
In-place updates are limited to description,
outputFileFormat, resultLocation, freeformTags,
and definedTags; name, compartmentId,
scheduleRecurrences, timeScheduled,
savedReportId, and queryProperties require
replacement and are rejected before OCI
mutation.
Delete retains the finalizer until GetSchedule
confirms the schedule no longer exists.
end note
note right of delete_pending
delete policy: required
delete observe: GetSchedule or ListSchedules
delete targets: DELETED
end note
@enduml
